5|$|Although <b>hot</b> <b>chocolate</b> is {{generally}} consumed for pleasure, the beverage confers several potential health benefits. A 2003 study from Cornell University found that cocoa contains {{large amounts of}} antioxidants that may help prevent cancer. Also, it has been demonstrated that the cocoa bean helps with digestion. From the 16th to 19th centuries, <b>hot</b> <b>chocolate</b> was valued as a medicine {{as well as a}} drink.|$|E
5|$|In 2012 Andrew 'Freddie' Flintoff {{broke the}} world record for the fastest time to drink a <b>hot</b> <b>chocolate</b> (5.45 seconds).|$|E
5|$|In the United States and Canada, {{the drink}} is popular in instant form, made {{with hot water}} or milk from a packet {{containing}} mostly cocoa powder, sugar, and dry milk. This is the thinner of the two main variations. It is very sweet and may be topped with marshmallows, whipped cream, {{or a piece of}} solid chocolate. <b>Hot</b> <b>chocolate</b> was first brought to North America as early as the 17th century by the Dutch, but the first time colonists began selling <b>hot</b> <b>chocolate</b> was around 1755. Traditionally, <b>hot</b> <b>chocolate</b> has been associated with cold weather, winter, and dessert in the United States and Canada.|$|E
